Romaike Middendorp (Data Scientist at XploData)

17-02-2020

Introduction

This notebook provides a quick starting point for participants of the Datathon KUL 2020 working with spatial data. This notebooks covers the very basics of handling spatial data in R and is accompanied by a workshop on Monday 17 February at the KUL.

This notebooks uses spatial data from three data sources: Telraam data on traffic, Leuvenair data on air quality and Garmon weather data. All data and additional information concerning the data can be found at: https://lstat.kuleuven.be/Datathon2020/data.

Spatail data objects in R

Telraam data

You’ll start by retrieving the active road segments in the Telraam data. These data can be accessed through this API: https://telraam-api.net/.

Active road segments are available in GeoJSON format. We load the data directly using the sf package, which is the successor of the well-established sp package. It does a great job at handling spatial data (also in GeoJSON format). The st_read function creates a data frame with a geometry list-column.

# Load libraries
library(tidyverse)

We can visualize the road segments, using the tmap package. Assign the spatial object to the tm_shape function and add a mapping from visual properties to variables. Here we map the number of cars that passed by in the last hour to the col argument. To create an interactive html map, use the view mode.

# Load library
library(tmap)

# Set mode to view
tmap_mode('view')
## tmap mode set to interactive viewing
# Set spatial object and type
tm_shape(active_sf) + 
  tm_lines(col = "car", scale = 3)

Telraam contains road segments over the whole of Flanders. Presumable, you’ll be interested in only the roads that are located in the city of Leuven. To filter out road segments outside of Leuven, you can use the method intersect.

First, let’s get the spatial boundaries of the city of Leuven. GADM is a useful open source that provides maps and spatial data for all countries and their sub-divisions: https://gadm.org/download_country_v3.html.

municipalities <- readRDS("data/gadm36_BEL_4_sf.rds")
leuven <- municipalities %>% filter(NAME_4 == "Leuven")

Now, we can filter the active road segments using the boundaries of Leuven from GADM. There are 133 unique active road segments in Leuven.

active_leuven <- active_sf[leuven, op = st_intersects]
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar
length(unique(active_leuven$id))
## [1] 133
# Remove duplicate roads
active_leuven <- active_leuven %>%
  arrange(id, last_data_package) %>%
  distinct(active_leuven, id, .keep_all = TRUE)

A new road segments sf object now only contains roads for the city of Leuven. You can map these with tmap.

# Load library
library(tmap)
tmap_mode('view')
## tmap mode set to interactive viewing
tm_shape(active_leuven) + 
  tm_lines(col = "car", scale = 3)

Retrieve Telraam reports for road segments in Leuven

Now that you have the spatial data for road segments loaded into R, you can take a look at the observed traffic on these roads.

The Telraam API provides reports with hourly observations on traffic for each segment. You can write a for loop to retrieve hourly reports for a given time interval for all the segment IDs in Leuven.

library(jsonlite)
## 
## Attaching package: 'jsonlite'
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     flatten
library(httr)
# First get a list of segment IDs in Leuven
segment_ids_leuven <- unique(active_leuven$id)

# Set the parameters for the POST request
headers <- c("Content-Type" = "application/json")

params <- '{
    "time_start": "2019-12-01 00:00",
    "time_end": "2019-12-07 23:59",
    "level": "segments",
    "format":"per-hour"
}'

# Initialize an empty data frame to store the Telraam data
reports <- data.frame()

# For each segment ID in Leuven do:
for (i in 1:length(segment_ids_leuven)){
  # build a request for each segment id:
  request <- httr::POST(url = paste0("https://telraam-api.net/v0/reports/", segment_ids_leuven[i]), 
    httr::add_headers(.headers = headers), body = params)
  # retrieve the API response
  response <- content(request, "text", encoding = "UTF-8")
  # flatten the data into a temporary data frame
  report_tmp <- fromJSON(response, flatten = TRUE) %>%
    data.frame()
  # bind the retrieved data into final data frame
  reports <- rbind(reports, report_tmp)
}

# Clean the column names
names(reports) <- str_replace(names(reports), "report.", "")

# Convert segment IDs to numeric (in stead of character)
reports <- reports %>%
  mutate(segment_id = as.numeric(segment_id))

# Check out your work!
head(reports)

The reports date frame now contains hourly measurements of traffic for 85 of Leuven’s road segments. You can plot the traffic counts over time by using a “tidy” approach. You start with cleaning the date time variable to a POSIXct format (i.e., a standard DateTime format in R) and then gathering the data to a long table where 1. each variable forms a column, 2.each observation forms a row, and 3. each type of observational unit forms a table (the three ‘rules’ of tidy data frames).

# Clean the date time value using the lubridate ymd_hm function
library(lubridate)
## 
## Attaching package: 'lubridate'
## The following object is masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     date
reports$date <- ymd_hm(reports$date, tz = "Europe/Paris")

# Get data in tidy format, by transforming the wide data frame to a long with count per 'vehicile' type
reports_long <- reports %>%
  select(1:7) %>%
  gather(key = "type", value = "count", 4:7) 
head(reports_long)
##   segment_id                date pct_up       type count
## 1      80828 2019-12-01 09:00:00   0.33 pedestrian     0
## 2      80828 2019-12-01 10:00:00   0.79 pedestrian     1
## 3      80828 2019-12-01 11:00:00   0.79 pedestrian     4
## 4      80828 2019-12-01 12:00:00   0.79 pedestrian     2
## 5      80828 2019-12-01 13:00:00   0.79 pedestrian     0
## 6      80828 2019-12-01 14:00:00   0.79 pedestrian     0
# Sample 6 random segmets for plotting
sample_segments <- sample(reports$segment_id, 6)

# Filter the reports on day and segment_id to show only a subset of all data
reports_long_sub <- reports_long %>% 
  filter(day(date) == 1 & segment_id %in% sample_segments)

# Plot date vs. traffic count, assign the color the the 'vehicile' type. Use facet wrap on segment id to get a plot per street segment
ggplot(reports_long_sub, aes(x = date, y = count, col = type)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~segment_id, ncol = 2, scales = "free")

Leuvenair data

Data collected by 116 sensors in and around Leuven are collected over two years. These data can be downloaded via this link: https://data.leuvenair.be/data-l.html.

The locations of air stations can be retrieved from the online JSON file and converted to a sf object by assigning the latitude and longitude coordinate columns in st_as_sf function. Keep stations where export equals 1.

air_stations <- fromJSON("https://data.leuvenair.be/data/LEUVENAIRmeta_final.json") 

# Select only where Export = 1 and convert to sf object
air_stations <- air_stations %>% 
  mutate_at(c(1:5, 11:17), as.numeric) %>% #'SDS011ID', 'INDUSTRY', 'WOODSTOVES', 'TRAFFIC', 'SVL', 'NO2_CN'
  filter(EXPORT == 1) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c('LON', 'LAT'))

st_crs(air_stations) <- "+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs"

First, filter these out. Additionally, not all air stations are present in the measurements for December, so also remove these.

# Filter out duplicate station IDs by selecting only first row grouped per sensor ID
air_stations <- air_stations %>%
  filter(SDS011ID %in% unique(air_stations$SDS011ID)) %>%
  group_by(SDS011ID) %>%
  filter(row_number()==1)

With the leaflet package you can quickly create an interactive plot of air stations on an Open Street Map background to see were stations are located. By using the addCircleMarkers and assigning the air stations, the locations are plotted as dots on the map.

library(leaflet)
library(htmltools)
leaflet() %>%
  addTiles(group = "OSM") %>% 
  addCircleMarkers(data = air_stations, radius = 2, label = ~paste0('Station ID: ', htmlEscape(SDS011ID)),
                   color = 'darkblue') 
tmap_mode('view')

tm_shape(active_leuven) + 
  tm_lines(col = "car", scale = 3) +
  tm_shape(air_stations) +
  tm_dots(col = 'darkblue')

Leuvenair P2.5 measurements

The spatial data on Leuvenair stations is loaded into R. Time to look at the air quality measurements. You start here with the full data dump from 2019. Given the amount of observations and the memory limitations of R run on your personal laptop, you can start by filtering the data to a selected time interval. By cleaning the DATEUTC variable to a date time format allows you to filter on the first week of December 2019.

# Read in the full data dump 2019
air <- read.csv('data/LEUVENAIRfulldump2019.csv', stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Subset airquality data to the first week of december
air <- air %>% 
  mutate(DATEUTC = ymd_hms(DATEUTC, tz = "UTC")) %>%
  filter(month(DATEUTC) == 12 & day(DATEUTC) %in% c(1:7)) %>% #%in% c(1:5)
  arrange(SDS011ID, DATEUTC)
str(air)

The observations from the different stations come from irregular time intervals. Additionally, we see some unusal high peaks in the PM2.5 measurements for some stations that were not measured in oter stations.

You start with cleaning and aggregating the Leuvenair data so that you could later join them to other data sources for analysis. First, create a date time vector with regular time intervals per second starting at 1 December through 7 December (i.e., the selected time interval). You cap high PM2.5 observations off at an arbitrary value of 125 to prevent visualizations from looking skewed. This is not a correct way to treat these ‘outlier’ measurements and you should tink about a better way to deal with these outliers.

# Crete a regular time interval of seconds between 1 Dec - 7 Dec
dt_seq <- seq(as.POSIXct("2019-12-01 00:00:00 UTC"),
              as.POSIXct("2019-12-07 23:59:59 UTC"),
              by = 1)
head(dt_seq)
## [1] "2019-12-01 00:00:00 CET" "2019-12-01 00:00:01 CET"
## [3] "2019-12-01 00:00:02 CET" "2019-12-01 00:00:03 CET"
## [5] "2019-12-01 00:00:04 CET" "2019-12-01 00:00:05 CET"
# Arbitrary capping off PM2.5 measurements above 100 to 100
air <- air %>%
  mutate(PM2.5 = ifelse(PM2.5 > 125, 125, PM2.5))

You then create a data frame with the regular second interval sequence for each of the sensor IDs in the Leuvenair data. Then you join the full date time data frame to the Leuvenair data using left_join. There are a lot of blanks, but you will solve this in the next step.

air_full <- data.frame(DATEUTC = dt_seq,
                  SDS011ID = rep(unique(air$SDS011ID), each = length(dt_seq))) %>%
  left_join(air[, c(1,4,5)], by = c("DATEUTC", "SDS011ID"))
head(air_full)

The regular spaced data frame created above (i.e., time intervals of 1 second) now contains all the observed air quality data of the Leuven sensors. You implement a rolling median over the PM2.5 measurements to obtain the hourly median for station. Here, you use the rollapply function from the zoo package. This package contains a set of very useful methods to work with time series in R. This step takes quite some time but will reduce the number of observations to keep in memory.

PM2.5zoo <- zoo(PM2.5wide[,-1], PM2.5wide$DATEUTC)    

# Apply rollapply function to calculate hourly median
PM2.5zoo_med <- rollapply(PM2.5zoo, width = 3599, 
                          FUN = function(x) median(x, na.rm = TRUE), by = 3600, 
                          by.column = TRUE, partial = TRUE, fill = NA, align = "right")

dt_sel <- seq(as.POSIXct("2019-12-01 00:00:00 UTC"),
              as.POSIXct("2019-12-07 23:59:59 UTC"),
              by = (60*60))

# Determine the index at which hourly measruments are in the dataset
ind <- which(index(PM2.5zoo_med) %in% dt_sel)

# Select only these measuremnts
PM2.5zoo_med <- PM2.5zoo_med[ind]
summary(PM2.5zoo_med)

Spatial data on weather stations is available in the data. You can retrieve the unique lat/lon coordiantes for weather stations from the data. Transform this dataset to sf object and plot it on an interactive map together with air station locations. Adding layers control allows you to toggle on and off the base and overlay groups you assign (i.e., provider tiles and circle markers).

# Get unique coorindates of meteo stations and convert to sf object
meteo_stations <- meteo %>%
  distinct(ID, LON, LAT) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c('LON', 'LAT'))

# Create an interactive leaflet map
leaflet() %>%
  addTiles(group = "OSM") %>% 
  addProviderTiles("CartoDB", group = "Carto") %>% 
  addCircleMarkers(data = meteo_stations, radius = 2, label = ~paste0('Station ID: ', htmlEscape(ID)),
                   color = 'navy',  group = "Meteo stations")  %>%
  addCircleMarkers(data = air_stations, radius = 2, label =  ~paste0('Station ID: ', htmlEscape(SDS011ID)),
                   color = 'red',  group = "Air stations") %>%
  addLayersControl(baseGroups = c("Carto", "OSM"),
                   overlayGroups = c("Meteo stations", "Air stations"))

Spatial operations on vector data

Distances between objects

Determine which air quality stations are closest to active road segments in Leuven. First calculate a buffer of 500 m around each air quality station. Since the CRS of both data sets are unprojected, we first need to project these to a metric CRS, such as Lambert 2008 projection using spTransform.

# Air stations as sp object
rownames(air_stations) <- air_stations$SDS011ID
air_stations_sp <- as(air_stations, "Spatial")

# Road segments as sp object
rownames(active_leuven) <- active_leuven$id
active_leuven_sp <- as(active_leuven, "Spatial")

# Load geospehere library
library(geosphere)
## 
## Attaching package: 'geosphere'
## The following object is masked from 'package:htmltools':
## 
##     span
# dist2Line calculates a distance matrix for each point to its closest line segment
dist.mat <- dist2Line(p = air_stations_sp, line = active_leuven_sp)

# Convert to data frame
dist_df <- data.frame(dist.mat)  

# Match station IDs
dist_df$station_id <- air_stations$SDS011ID

# Merge with segment IDs
active_air <- merge(dist_df, active_leuven, by.x = "ID", by.y = "row.names")

Spatial joins: find nearest neighbors

The st_nn function in the nngeo package allows you to find the nearest neighbor for each meteo and weather station. Alternatively, using st_join you can spatially join two sf objects together, in this case based on the nearest neighboring stations.

# Load library
library(nngeo)

# Find nearest neightbor of each station
nn_stations_dist <- st_nn(air_stations, meteo_stations, k = 1, returnDist = TRUE)
## projected points
## 
  |                                                                       
  |                                                                 |   0%
  |                                                                       
  |=================================================================| 100%
# Alternatively you can join to points together
nn_stations_join <- st_join(air_stations, meteo_stations, st_nn, k = 1)
## projected points
## 
  |                                                                       
  |                                                                 |   0%
  |                                                                       
  |=================================================================| 100%

Now that the spatial data are loaded, you can have a look at the median weather observations for December. Calculate daily weather medians for the city of Leuven (humidity, windspeed, and rainin) and left_join the daily median PM2.5 observations from the Leuvenair data. Convert the data to tidy format for plotting.

# Filter for December 2019
meteo_2019_09 <- meteo %>%
  mutate(DATEUTC = ymd_hms(DATEUTC, tz = "UTC")) %>%
  filter(month(DATEUTC) == 12 & year(DATEUTC) == 2019)

# Load daily median PM2.5 measurments from the Leuvenair data
air_med <- read.csv('data/LEUVENAIRfulldumpMedian.csv', stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Filter these for December 2019 as well
air_med <- air_med %>% 
  mutate(DATEUTC = ymd_hms(DATEUTC, tz = "UTC")) %>%
  filter(month(DATEUTC) == 12 & year(DATEUTC) == 2019)

# Group by date to get the median weather measurements by day and join air data
meteo_2019_09_med <- meteo_2019_09 %>%
  group_by (DATEUTC) %>%
  summarise(HUMIDITY = median(HUMIDITY, na.rm = TRUE),
            WINDSPEEDKMH = median(WINDSPEEDKMH, na.rm = TRUE),
            RAININ = median(RAININ, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  left_join(air_med %>% select(DATEUTC, PM2.5)) %>%
  # Create a long 'tidy' table by applying gathering
  gather(key = "VARIABLE", value = "MEDIAN", 2:5)
## Joining, by = "DATEUTC"

Plot the weather and PM2.5 data to see if we can detect interesting trends for the city of Leuven during December 2019. PM2.5 peaks seem to occur on days with little rain and wind.

ggplot(meteo_2019_09_med, aes(x = DATEUTC, y = MEDIAN)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~VARIABLE, scales = "free", ncol = 1)

Quick spatiotemporal analysis of Leuvenair data

The data collected by the different sensors in Leuven have a temporal, spatial and data component. Making them very challenging (en exciting) to work with! R provides several tools to work with high-dimensional data like these. Here, you will make a quick visualization of the fine particles in the Leuvenair dataset for the first week of December using the spacetime package. Some other useful packages to look into might be rggobi and plotKML for visual inspection of the data. The observations have already been loaded and prepared above (i.e., hourly medians).

First, you create a space-time full grid object by assigning a spatial, time and data component.

# Get PM2.5 observations in vector format
PM2.5dats <- data.frame(vals = as.vector(t(PM2.5zoo_med)))

# Filter on the IDs in the air data
air_stations_sp <- air_stations %>% 
  filter(SDS011ID %in% unique(air$SDS011ID)) 

# Air stations as sp object
air_stations_sp <- as(air_stations_sp, "Spatial")

# Create STFDF object
library(spacetime)
PM2.5st <- STFDF(sp = air_stations_sp,
                 time = index(PM2.5zoo_med),
                 data = PM2.5dats)

You create an visual representation of the spacetime object by applying the stplot function on the space-time grid.

# Visualise spatiotemporal data
airPal <- colorRampPalette(c('springgreen1', 'sienna3', 'gray5'))(5)
# 
# Use stplot to create a spacetime visual
stplot(PM2.5st, mode = 'xt',
       col.regions = colorRampPalette(airPal)(15),
       scales = list(x = list(rot = 45)),
       ylab = '', xlab = '', main = '')
